      <p>Guinea fowl are sometimes raised as livestock for their meat and eggs. Guinea fowl are hardy birds native to Africa, and are prized for their delicious meat and flavorful eggs. They are also considered to be low maintenance birds, as they are able to forage for their own food and do not require special housing or feeding arrangements. Guinea fowl are often raised in free-range or semi-free-range systems, and are often used as a more sustainable and natural alternative to traditional poultry species. The meat of guinea fowl is considered a delicacy and is used in a variety of dishes, while the eggs are considered to be a healthy alternative to chicken eggs and are used in cooking and baking. Guinea fowl farming is practiced in many parts of the world, including Europe, Africa, and North America.</p>
      <p>Guinea fowl are not a suggested breed for those that live in suburban or urban areas since they are boisterous birds. They scare easily and will run around trying to escape while simultaneously sounding an alarm. Their call is harsh, loud, and repetitive.</p>
      <p>When the guinea ales make their alarm call, it sounds like a “chi-chi-chi” or a “kek-kek-kek.” The guinea hen makes a sound more like “buck-wheat buck-wheat.” They are also quick to defend themselves and their flock.</p>
      <p>Guinea fowl are a highly social breed and do best in a large flock. The flock does not need to be all guinea fowl, they do very well in a mixed flock of chickens or other birds.</p>
      <p>While guinea fowl and chickens generally get along, during the breeding season a guinea male may become more territorial. Guinea fowl and chickens can also cross breed and produce offspring.</p>

      <h2 class="sub-section-heading">Guinea Fowl Meat</h2>

      <div class="floated-media float-right">
          <img src="GuineaFowlMeat.jpg" alt="Guinea Fowl Meat" />
          <% ' No caption in original, add if needed: <p class="media-caption">Your Caption</p> %>
      </div>

      <p>Guinea fowl meat has been considered a delicacy for such a long time. They were well-known to Romans and were often the highlight course of their luxurious feasts.</p>
      <p>Guinea fowl meat is a type of poultry that is becoming increasingly popular in many countries. It is considered a lean meat that is lower in fat and calories compared to other poultry, such as chicken. It has a unique flavor that is described as a combination of chicken, turkey, and game birds.</p>
      <p>The meat is tender and has a mild, nutty flavor that is versatile enough to be used in a variety of dishes, from soups and stews to roasted meats and poultry dishes. It can be cooked using a variety of cooking methods, including grilling, roasting, and sautéing.</p>
      <p>In terms of nutrition, guinea fowl meat is a good source of protein, vitamins, and minerals, including vitamin B6, niacin, and phosphorus. It is also a good source of healthy monounsaturated and polyunsaturated fats, which can help to improve heart health and lower cholesterol levels.</p>

